			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I converted to Linux this past week, and I love it.  The learning curve is fairly steep, but most of the processes are so simple, that anyone familiar with DOS should figure it out.  For anyone just getting started, I can't recommend <a href="http://www.linuxquestions.org" target="_blank">www.linuxquestions.org</a> enough.  I've found nearly every answer to every stupid n00b question I had in those forums, and the people there are amazingly friendly and eager to truly help someone just starting out.  
<br />

<br />
As to your question:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Ok I just got and installed a second hard drive to my comp, it would be very simple to put linux on one and have windows remain on the other and just switch between the two drives correct?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, as a matter of fact, thats how I have my system currently set up, and I find it to be the easiest when each OS has their own drive.  A few points, however:
<br />

<br />
 - Install Windows first, especially if you're using XP.  Decide what drive you're going to put it on, install Windows to that drive, then do your Linux installation.  If you install Windows first, XP will copy itself over your bootloader and will in essence ruin your Linux installation.  Obviously (as Windows believes), you didn't really mean to have a non-MS operating system installed!  Why would you need something besides XP!?
<br />

<br />
 - When Windows is set up, install Linux to the other hard drive.  Linux will automatically configure (in most distros) a bootloader program (either Lilo or GRUB), which will make your computer have a menu when you boot it up of which operating system you would like to load. (Windows is recognized as DOS a lot of times, just FYI).
<br />

<br />
 - When you install Windows, think very hard on whether you want data to be shared between the operating systems.  If you do, I recommend FAT32.  Its -possible- to get Linux to recognize NTFS, but its very buggy and generally not a great idea.  I don't give a shit about crossing files over since I only use Windows for Win32 apps (I'm not advanced enough for WINE setup yet, oy), so it wasn't a big concern for me.
<br />

<br />
Hope this helps.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
