			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-weight: bold">Dual Hard Drive Dual Boot: The Klast Method</span>
<br />

<br />
The question of which to install first is usually academic.  For most people trying Linux the fist time Windows will already be on one hard drive.  So Linux will automatically be the second thing you install.
<br />

<br />
This method assumes you do not have 2 optical drives.  The trick I use involves going in to the BIOS and altering the boot order.  
<br />

<br />
When you install the new drive in the case put it on the IDE cable with your CDRom drive.  You will need to mess with the master slave jumpers.  
<br />

<br />
Now that you have one HD on each IDE channel turn on the computer and immediately go in to your BIOS.  Do not boot.  Do not pass go.  Do not collect 200 plat.
<br />

<br />
In the BIOS you need to first make sure the new drive arrangement is detected.  So BIOSs will have a handy auto detect function.  Yours may not.
<br />

<br />
Once the drives are all detected properly by the BIOS you need to change the boot order.  Typically it will be something like:  
<br />
1 FLOPPY 
<br />
2 CD 
<br />
3 IDE 0
<br />
Change the IDE channel to 1 if it is 0 or to 0 if it is 1.
<br />

<br />
Now you can exit the BIOS saving your changes and boot with your Linux install disk.
<br />

<br />
If you did it right when you get to the partitioning step of your install you will be informed that HAD is (whatever your new drive is) and HDB is formatted NTFS, or FAT32.  Pay attention to the drive sizes if you have no other way of telling the 2 drives apart.  If HAD is your windows drive, cancel the install and switch the boot IDE channel in your BIOS 
<br />

<br />
Once you get the install of Linux nearly done it will ask you to install a boot loader.  Go ahead and put GRUB or LILO on the Linux drive.  It should auto detect your windows drive and when you reboot you will be presented with a new boot menu which will give you the choice of booting in to Linux or windows.  
<br />

<br />
You can confidently put the boot loader on your Linux HD knowing that your windows HD remains untouched.   Even if you have a boot sector eating catastrophe your windows disk will be untouched by the Linux install process.  Also if you choose to get rid of Linux and go back to single boot you just switch your boot order back in the BIOS and you dont have the legacy boot loader left behind on the boot sector of your windows HD to prompt you every time you turn on the computer.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
